The '''Future Character of Conflict''' was a study produced by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|UK Ministry of Defence]]'s [[Development, Concepts and Doctrine Centre]] (DCDC).  It was undertaken alongside the Centre's [[Global Strategic Trends Programme]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The report details global trends that indicate increasing [[instability]] and growing opportunity for confrontation and group conflict.  [[State failure]], [[Extremism|extremists]], increased competition for resources and the changing global [[Balance of power in international relations|balance of power]] will dictate why, where and how conflict occurs.  The study concludes that the character of conflict will continue to evolve.  Though it is impossible to accurately predict the exact character of the future conflict, in many future operations the armed forces are likely to face a range of simultaneous threats and adversaries in an anarchic and extended operating area.

This report is now outdated, and is replaced by the document Future Operating Environment 2035.(See [https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/484861/20151203-DCDC_FOE_35.pdf]<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486301/20151210-Archived_DCDC_FCOC.pdf</ref>

